 {"id": "franken_networkx-srgdiam", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] is_strongly_regular classified every K_n (n>=3) and C_3 as strongly regular; nx excludes them", "description": "nx.is_strongly_regular uses ``is_distance_regular(G) and diameter(G) == 2`` \u2014 the diameter-2 requirement excludes complete graphs (K_n diameter 1) and C_3 (=K_3). The Rust _fnx.is_strongly_regular_rust implementation missed this requirement and returned True for every K_n tested (K3..K7) plus C_3 where nx returns False. Replaced the Rust delegation with the nx-equivalent ``is_distance_regular(G) and diameter(G) == 2`` formula and added explicit directed/multigraph rejection. Verified: K3..K7 now False (match nx), C3 False (match), C4/C5 True (match), Petersen True (match), DiGraph/MultiGraph raise NetworkXNotImplemented.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T18:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T18:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T18:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Implement via distance_regular + diameter-2", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-daglongweight", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] dag_longest_path/dag_longest_path_length ignored edge weights", "description": "The Rust _raw_dag_longest_path computed the longest edge-count path, not the longest weighted path \u2014 so on a graph with edges (0->1, w=2), (1->2, w=3), (0->2, w=10) fnx returned [0, 1, 2] (length=2 by edge count) while nx correctly returned [0, 2] (length=10 by weight sum). The wrapper only delegated to nx when the ``weight`` kwarg differed from 'weight' default, so the default case \u2014 which is the COMMON case \u2014 silently returned wrong answers whenever weights existed. Added _dag_has_weight_edge_attr probe that checks whether any edge carries the weight attribute; when True, delegate to nx. Unweighted graphs still take the Rust fast path.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T18:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T18:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T18:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate when edges carry weight attr", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-tcreflnone", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] transitive_closure raised TypeError on reflexive=None (nx accepts it)", "description": "nx.transitive_closure treats ``reflexive`` as a tri-value flag (None / False / True) \u2014 None maps semantically to the historical default (equivalent to False). The Rust _raw_transitive_closure was strictly typed bool and raised ``TypeError: argument 'reflexive': 'None' is not an instance of 'bool'``. Fixed by gating the Rust fast-path on ``reflexive is False`` and delegating every other value (True AND None) to nx; the Rust call now also passes literal False rather than the raw parameter.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T18:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T18:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T18:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Gate on reflexive is False", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-voronoicell", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] voronoi_cells ignored weight kwarg AND assigned nodes to wrong center", "description": "The Rust voronoi_cells_rust (a) did not accept the ``weight`` kwarg \u2014 weighted graphs silently ran an unweighted BFS-based Voronoi partition \u2014 and (b) assigned some nodes to the wrong center even on the unweighted case. Concrete failing example: a 4-node cycle 0->1->2->3->0 plus the shortcut edge 0->2(w=2), centers {0, 2}. Node 3 is one hop from center 2 but two hops from center 0, so it should land in center 2's cell; fnx put it in center 0's cell. Delegate to nx for the full weighted-Dijkstra implementation; wrapped via a private _voronoi_cells_impl so the public symbol stays PY_WRAPPER.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx via _voronoi_cells_impl", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-ndbndset", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] node_boundary returned list; nx returns set", "description": "nx.node_boundary returns a set of nodes incident to the boundary between nbunch1 and (optionally) nbunch2. The direct re-export of the Rust binding returned a plain list \u2014 callers doing set operations (``{x} == boundary``, ``boundary.issubset(...)``, intersection, union) silently broke. Wrap with set coercion in the Python wrapper.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T19:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Coerce to set", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
